    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Context Window Problem in Standard Chunking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Standard chunking splits a document before embedding: each chunk is encoded independently with no knowledge of adjacent text. This discards cross-chunk context \u2014 pronouns lose their referents, section headings are orphaned from their content, and named entities appear in isolation. Late Chunking, introduced by Jina AI in 2024, inverts this: encode the full document first with a long-context model, then pool the resulting token representations per chunk boundary. Every chunk embedding is contextualised by the whole document."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Early vs late chunking comparison diagram"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How Late Chunking Works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Late Chunking requires a long-context embedding model that returns per-token representations (not just a pooled [CLS] vector). The algorithm is: (1) tokenise the entire document; (2) identify chunk boundary positions in token space; (3) run the full token sequence through the encoder; (4) mean-pool the token representations within each chunk span to produce one vector per chunk. The resulting vectors are contextually aware yet each represents its own text span for ANN retrieval."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nfrom transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModel\n\n# Jina's long-context embedding model (8192 token window)\nmodel_name = \"jinaai/jina-embeddings-v2-base-en\"\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name, trust_remote_code=True)\nmodel = AutoModel.from_pretrained(model_name, trust_remote_code=True)\nmodel.eval()\n\ndef late_chunking_embed(document: str, chunk_boundaries: list[tuple[int, int]]) -> list[list[float]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    chunk_boundaries: list of (start_char, end_char) tuples.\n    Returns one embedding vector per chunk, each contextualised by full doc.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Tokenise full document\n    encoding = tokenizer(document, return_tensors=\"pt\", return_offsets_mapping=True, truncation=True, max_length=8192)\n    offset_mapping = encoding[\"offset_mapping\"][0]  # (n_tokens, 2)\n\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        outputs = model(**{k: v for k, v in encoding.items() if k != \"offset_mapping\"})\n    token_embeds = outputs.last_hidden_state[0]  # (n_tokens, hidden_dim)\n\n    chunk_vecs = []\n    for char_start, char_end in chunk_boundaries:\n        # Find which tokens fall within this character span\n        mask = (offset_mapping[:, 0] >= char_start) & (offset_mapping[:, 1] <= char_end)\n        span_tokens = token_embeds[mask]\n        if span_tokens.shape[0] == 0:\n            continue\n        # Mean pool over the span's token vectors\n        chunk_vec = span_tokens.mean(dim=0)\n        chunk_vec = F.normalize(chunk_vec, dim=-1)\n        chunk_vecs.append(chunk_vec.tolist())\n\n    return chunk_vecs\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Building Chunk Boundaries from a Text Splitter"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangChain text splitters return strings, not character offsets. To use late chunking, map each chunk back to its position in the original document using string search. A simple approach is to scan the original text for each chunk's content and record the start/end offsets."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain_text_splitters import RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter\n\ndef get_chunk_boundaries(document: str, chunks: list[str]) -> list[tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"Map chunk strings back to (start_char, end_char) positions in the original document.\"\"\"\n    boundaries = []\n    search_start = 0\n    for chunk in chunks:\n        idx = document.find(chunk.strip(), search_start)\n        if idx == -1:\n            # Fallback: partial match on first 60 chars\n            idx = document.find(chunk[:60].strip(), search_start)\n        if idx != -1:\n            boundaries.append((idx, idx + len(chunk)))\n            search_start = idx + len(chunk) - 50  # small overlap for safety\n    return boundaries\n\ndocument = open(\"research_paper.txt\").read()\nsplitter = RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(chunk_size=512, chunk_overlap=50)\nchunks = splitter.split_text(document)\n\nboundaries = get_chunk_boundaries(document, chunks)\nchunk_embeddings = late_chunking_embed(document, boundaries)\n\nprint(f\"Created {len(chunk_embeddings)} contextualised chunk embeddings\")\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Indexing Late-Chunked Embeddings in a Vector Store"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The resulting chunk vectors are ordinary float32 arrays and slot into any vectorstore that accepts pre-computed embeddings. Chroma and FAISS both support add_embeddings methods that bypass internal encoding. Store the chunk text and source metadata alongside so the retriever can return the original text."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain_community.vectorstores import FAISS\nfrom langchain_core.documents import Document\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Build Document objects from chunks + their late-chunking vectors\ndocs = [\n    Document(page_content=chunk, metadata={\"source\": \"paper.txt\", \"chunk_idx\": i})\n    for i, chunk in enumerate(chunks)\n]\nembeddings_array = np.array(chunk_embeddings, dtype=np.float32)  # (n_chunks, dim)\n\n# FAISS from_embeddings accepts pre-computed vectors\ntext_embedding_pairs = list(zip([d.page_content for d in docs], chunk_embeddings))\nmetadatas = [d.metadata for d in docs]\n\nvectorstore = FAISS.from_embeddings(\n    text_embeddings=text_embedding_pairs,\n    embedding=None,           # no encoder needed \u2014 we supply vectors directly\n    metadatas=metadatas\n)\n\n# Query requires the same embedding model to encode the query\ndef encode_query(query: str) -> list[float]:\n    enc = tokenizer(query, return_tensors=\"pt\", truncation=True, max_length=512)\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        out = model(**enc)\n    q_vec = out.last_hidden_state[0].mean(dim=0)\n    return F.normalize(q_vec, dim=-1).tolist()\n\nquery_vec = encode_query(\"What baseline does the paper compare against?\")\nresults = vectorstore.similarity_search_by_vector(query_vec, k=5)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When Late Chunking Outperforms Standard Chunking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Late chunking has the highest impact on documents with heavy coreference \u2014 academic papers with frequent pronoun use, narrative text, technical documentation where section headings define the context for all subsequent paragraphs. The improvement is measurable on recall@k: late chunking typically gains 3\u20138 percentage points on dense coreference corpora versus early chunking with the same embedding model."
          }
        ]
      },
